WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.491 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.491 --> 00:00:07.485 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.485 --> 00:00:17.480 align:middle line:90%


00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:20.870 align:middle line:84%
>> All of us are
familiar with dogs.

00:00:20.870 --> 00:00:22.608 align:middle line:84%
We've all lived in
and amongst dogs

00:00:22.608 --> 00:00:24.400 align:middle line:84%
even if we're not dog
lovers or dog owners.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:27.700 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:29.923 align:middle line:84%
We know lots of
dogs as individuals.

00:00:29.923 --> 00:00:33.790 align:middle line:90%


00:00:33.790 --> 00:00:36.970 align:middle line:84%
Every single one of them
biologically is a gray wolf.

00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:38.740 align:middle line:84%
They're not related
to gray wolves.

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:40.570 align:middle line:90%
They actually are gray wolves.

00:00:40.570 --> 00:00:43.830 align:middle line:90%


00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:45.660 align:middle line:84%
Some of the breeds you
can really see that.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:47.077 align:middle line:84%
It's easy to
understand if we see,

00:00:47.077 --> 00:00:48.870 align:middle line:84%
like, any of the
Alaskan sled dog type

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.550 align:middle line:84%
breeds or we see even
a German shepherd.

00:00:50.550 --> 00:00:52.350 align:middle line:84%
You can look at that and
go, I see the wolf in that.

00:00:52.350 --> 00:00:53.880 align:middle line:84%
But you start to
get down to, like,

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:57.300 align:middle line:84%
a Shih Tzu or a pit bull
or a little terrier,

00:00:57.300 --> 00:00:59.280 align:middle line:84%
and you don't see the
gray wolf anymore.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:02.570 align:middle line:84%
You see that domestication
has changed them.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:05.600 align:middle line:90%


00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:09.350 align:middle line:84%
The gray wolf is Canis lupus,
and the domesticated dog

00:01:09.350 --> 00:01:11.240 align:middle line:90%
is Canis lupus familiaris.

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:15.110 align:middle line:84%
And we add that trinomial part,
that last epithet to its name,

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:17.360 align:middle line:84%
to designate that it's
been domesticated.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:19.730 align:middle line:10%
So you can see that as
something's moved away

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:22.970 align:middle line:10%
from wild nature and
its diet is changed

00:01:22.970 --> 00:01:25.490 align:middle line:10%
and its environmental
conditions are changed

00:01:25.490 --> 00:01:28.880 align:middle line:10%
and, most importantly, probably,
sexual selection becomes

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:29.870 align:middle line:10%
a factor--

00:01:29.870 --> 00:01:31.760 align:middle line:10%
we think a lot about
natural selection,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:33.410 align:middle line:10%
how the environment shapes us.

00:01:33.410 --> 00:01:36.320 align:middle line:10%
What we forget is the
incredible power wielded usually

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:39.710 align:middle line:10%
by female of a species
to select mates,

00:01:39.710 --> 00:01:43.820 align:middle line:10%
and that will drive radical
changes in phenotypes.

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:47.330 align:middle line:10%
With domestication, we get
into artificial selection.

00:01:47.330 --> 00:01:49.545 align:middle line:10%
So we change the environment.

00:01:49.545 --> 00:01:51.045 align:middle line:10%
So it's no longer
natural selection.

00:01:51.045 --> 00:01:53.120 align:middle line:10%
It's not the
environmental pressure.

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:55.010 align:middle line:10%
And we become the
sexual selectors, who

00:01:55.010 --> 00:01:57.020 align:middle line:10%
we want to breed,
and over time, we

00:01:57.020 --> 00:01:59.900 align:middle line:10%
can-- in actually a fairly
short period of biological time,

00:01:59.900 --> 00:02:05.090 align:middle line:10%
we can take a gray wolf
and turn it to a chihuahua.

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:07.768 align:middle line:84%
When we talk about a
purebred dog, the dog that

00:02:07.768 --> 00:02:10.310 align:middle line:84%
comes with papers, the dog that
can get into the Kennel Club,

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:13.220 align:middle line:84%
that's actually a very
genetically weak animal.

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:16.310 align:middle line:10%
It's come from a very
restricted gene pool.

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:18.680 align:middle line:84%
So if it was a German
shepherd, they're

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:21.240 align:middle line:84%
going to end up with hip
dysplasia almost every time.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:24.410 align:middle line:84%
There are pugs where
their entire face has

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:25.805 align:middle line:90%
been sort of crushed forward.

00:02:25.805 --> 00:02:26.930 align:middle line:90%
They can't breathe anymore.

00:02:26.930 --> 00:02:29.482 align:middle line:84%
These are artifacts of
this sexual selection

00:02:29.482 --> 00:02:30.690 align:middle line:90%
we were talking about before.

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:33.320 align:middle line:84%
So somebody says, I
like a German shepherd

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:36.640 align:middle line:84%
with hips that are lower than
its shoulder blades, let's say.

00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:39.210 align:middle line:10%
And over time, if you look at
pictures of German shepherds

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:41.180 align:middle line:10%
50 years ago, 60
years ago to today,

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:45.740 align:middle line:10%
you'll see that they've gotten
that aesthetic-- that aesthetic

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:49.060 align:middle line:10%
that people like in the German
shepherd has been selected for.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:50.930 align:middle line:10%
Oh, this female has it
and this male has it.

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:51.730 align:middle line:10%
Let's breed them.

00:02:51.730 --> 00:02:53.660 align:middle line:10%
Oh, now let's take puppies
and keep breeding that

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:54.710 align:middle line:10%
and keep breeding that.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:57.210 align:middle line:10%
So as we've done that, we've
ended up with these animals who

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:59.150 align:middle line:10%
have all of these
artifacts, these

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:02.510 align:middle line:10%
features that actually
impact their health.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:04.250 align:middle line:10%
We've done that with
a lot of species.

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:06.370 align:middle line:10%
We've done that with
cows and sheep and goats.

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:08.120 align:middle line:10%
And we've done that
with a host of plants.

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:10.970 align:middle line:10%
We're working on mushrooms
and bacteria and algae

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:13.550 align:middle line:10%
and all these things right
now, domesticating the world.

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:14.520 align:middle line:90%
In the process--

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:17.045 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we ever set
out to domesticate ourselves.

00:03:17.045 --> 00:03:18.170 align:middle line:90%
But in the process, we did.

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:53.733 align:middle line:90%


00:03:53.733 --> 00:03:56.400 align:middle line:84%
It's important to understand the
timeline that this has happened

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:57.960 align:middle line:90%
in, because human beings--

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:00.090 align:middle line:84%
we get new archaeological
evidence all the time.

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:03.540 align:middle line:84%
And now genomics and
genetics has shown us--

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:06.030 align:middle line:84%
we're able to peer a little
bit deeper into our origins.

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:08.010 align:middle line:84%
But we know that
we're at least--

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:10.800 align:middle line:84%
in our current form, we're
something like 300,000 years

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.620 align:middle line:90%
old as modern humans.

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:16.740 align:middle line:84%
But humans as a
genus, genus Homo,

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:18.720 align:middle line:90%
goes back a lot farther, right?

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.670 align:middle line:84%
And all of us were
hunter gatherers.

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:22.400 align:middle line:90%
That's our wild type.

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:24.150 align:middle line:84%
Most of us only interact
with human beings

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:25.120 align:middle line:90%
of the domestic type.

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:28.140 align:middle line:90%


00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:31.740 align:middle line:84%
But the wild type
hunts and gathers.

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:33.600 align:middle line:84%
Something between
10,000 and 14,000 years

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.430 align:middle line:90%
ago, human beings started--

00:04:35.430 --> 00:04:38.767 align:middle line:84%
in the Fertile Crescent,
started to plant things.

00:04:38.767 --> 00:04:40.350 align:middle line:84%
We started to-- we
went from this idea

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:42.150 align:middle line:90%
of tending to the wild.

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:45.360 align:middle line:84%
And this is not a surviving,
hand-to-mouth kind of a thing.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:48.210 align:middle line:84%
People have gotten very good
at getting food resources out

00:04:48.210 --> 00:04:51.280 align:middle line:84%
of their environment
and also interacting

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:53.280 align:middle line:84%
with the environment to
make it more productive.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:54.300 align:middle line:90%
We tended the wild.

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:57.190 align:middle line:84%
We were like gardeners
of the wild landscape.

00:04:57.190 --> 00:05:00.030 align:middle line:84%
But this idea to start
planting starts around 10,000

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:01.500 align:middle line:90%
to 14,000 years ago.

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:04.800 align:middle line:84%
And very quickly, we
shift away from being

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:10.943 align:middle line:84%
hunter gatherers in that area
of the world to being domestic.

00:05:10.943 --> 00:05:12.610 align:middle line:84%
This all starts, like,
10,000 years ago.

00:05:12.610 --> 00:05:15.880 align:middle line:84%
So again, if we took this
timeline, here's 300,000 years.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.290 align:middle line:84%
And this whole time,
we hunt and gather.

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:21.858 align:middle line:90%
And then 10,000 years ago--

00:05:21.858 --> 00:05:24.150 align:middle line:84%
and it's not like 10,000
years ago-- we call this thing

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:26.870 align:middle line:84%
the Neolithic Revolution,
the first planting.

00:05:26.870 --> 00:05:29.670 align:middle line:84%
It makes it sound like it just
caught fire and went around

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:30.030 align:middle line:90%
the world.

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:32.572 align:middle line:84%
I would point out that this is
not even a complete revolution

00:05:32.572 --> 00:05:33.630 align:middle line:90%
yet.

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:35.190 align:middle line:84%
There are people
all around the world

00:05:35.190 --> 00:05:36.791 align:middle line:90%
still hunting and gathering.

00:05:36.791 --> 00:05:39.293 align:middle line:90%


00:05:39.293 --> 00:05:40.710 align:middle line:84%
But once we start
planting, now we

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:42.810 align:middle line:90%
need to guard that area, right?

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:43.830 align:middle line:90%
We need to weed it.

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:45.048 align:middle line:90%
We need to till it.

00:05:45.048 --> 00:05:46.590 align:middle line:84%
We need to keep
animals away from it.

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:48.570 align:middle line:90%
So people start to settle down.

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:50.940 align:middle line:84%
And this is the first time
that we become sedentary.

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:54.080 align:middle line:90%


00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:56.810 align:middle line:84%
Very quickly, shockingly
fast, out of that

00:05:56.810 --> 00:05:58.910 align:middle line:84%
starts to emerge
the city-states.

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:00.890 align:middle line:84%
About 6,000, 7,000 years
ago, we start seeing

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:02.900 align:middle line:90%
the first city-states emerge.

00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:06.110 align:middle line:84%
And what we have now
is enough surplus food

00:06:06.110 --> 00:06:08.750 align:middle line:84%
to create an environment where
you can have a class of people

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:11.630 align:middle line:84%
who can sit at the top and
not have to forage anymore,

00:06:11.630 --> 00:06:12.898 align:middle line:90%
not have to hunt anymore.

00:06:12.898 --> 00:06:14.690 align:middle line:84%
In a hunter-gatherer
community, everybody's

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:18.650 align:middle line:84%
like a sovereign individual,
and it's an egalitarian system.

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:22.370 align:middle line:84%
Everyone does overlapping
jobs to make sure

00:06:22.370 --> 00:06:23.450 align:middle line:90%
that everyone's fed.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:24.470 align:middle line:90%
Everybody forages.

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:25.520 align:middle line:90%
Everybody hunts.

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.010 align:middle line:84%
The chief does, and the
runt of the litter does.

00:06:28.010 --> 00:06:31.130 align:middle line:84%
Everybody participates
equally and together.

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:32.930 align:middle line:84%
But now you have
this system where,

00:06:32.930 --> 00:06:35.120 align:middle line:84%
through growing
grains primarily--

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:37.030 align:middle line:84%
in Mesopotamia, we're
talking about wheat.

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:38.780 align:middle line:84%
But if we get over to
Asia, another center

00:06:38.780 --> 00:06:40.910 align:middle line:84%
of domestication, we're
talking about rice.

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:43.490 align:middle line:84%
If we go over to Mesoamerica,
we see another center

00:06:43.490 --> 00:06:46.490 align:middle line:84%
of domestication that arises
later based around maize

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:48.080 align:middle line:90%
or what you now call corn.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:50.390 align:middle line:84%
We can produce surplus
food by doing this.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:53.210 align:middle line:84%
This is the first time
human beings have more food

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:54.050 align:middle line:90%
than they can eat.

00:06:54.050 --> 00:06:56.670 align:middle line:90%


00:06:56.670 --> 00:07:01.470 align:middle line:84%
Hunter gatherers tend to have
this sort of daily subsistence

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:02.730 align:middle line:90%
or weekly subsistence, right?

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:05.700 align:middle line:84%
It's like we harvest
enough for what we need,

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:08.160 align:middle line:84%
and as it runs down, we go
out and we get more of it.

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:11.160 align:middle line:84%
The hunters go out when the meat
resource starts to be depleted.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:13.620 align:middle line:84%
The foragers go out when
the plant resource--

00:07:13.620 --> 00:07:16.650 align:middle line:84%
some is stored, but lots of
it's just sort of eaten up.

00:07:16.650 --> 00:07:19.620 align:middle line:84%
But for the first time, now we
have all this surplus grain.

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:21.690 align:middle line:90%
And now we can feed more people.

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:24.990 align:middle line:84%
So immediately what happens is
the population starts to grow.

00:07:24.990 --> 00:07:26.970 align:middle line:84%
And so you start to
have people settle down.

00:07:26.970 --> 00:07:30.150 align:middle line:84%
And then quickly, they
start to grow and multiply.

00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:32.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you start to
get a stratified society

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:35.275 align:middle line:84%
because you need somebody to
sort of watch over the grain.

00:07:35.275 --> 00:07:36.900 align:middle line:84%
And then you need
somebody to determine

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:38.282 align:middle line:90%
how to distribute the grain.

00:07:38.282 --> 00:07:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And then you've got to start
having rules about that.

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:42.330 align:middle line:84%
So now you've got to have
sort of a legal class.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:43.410 align:middle line:84%
And, well, how do
you enforce that?

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:44.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, now you need
an enforcement class.

00:07:44.890 --> 00:07:46.307 align:middle line:84%
Well, who sits on
the top of that?

00:07:46.307 --> 00:07:49.320 align:middle line:84%
You start to quickly develop
a hierarchical system.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:51.930 align:middle line:84%
Living in a hierarchical
structure where

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:55.020 align:middle line:84%
you have a ruling class and
a policing and military class

00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:57.440 align:middle line:84%
and an educational
class and then you

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:59.190 align:middle line:84%
get down to sort of a
worker class, that's

00:07:59.190 --> 00:08:00.900 align:middle line:90%
not our natural way of being.

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.250 align:middle line:84%
We can make it work
to some degree,

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.130 align:middle line:84%
but that's not our
biological norm.

00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:22.430 align:middle line:90%


00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:25.670 align:middle line:84%
>> Conquistadors and other
colonizers were not nice,

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:26.470 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:29.560 align:middle line:84%
We were going enslaving people
and clear cutting forests

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:31.900 align:middle line:84%
and really just destroying
nature, destroying people.

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:33.204 align:middle line:90%
We were killing machines.

00:08:33.204 --> 00:08:43.190 align:middle line:90%


00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:45.920 align:middle line:84%
I would have thought that those
people would have just thought

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:47.810 align:middle line:90%
that we're evil.

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:51.260 align:middle line:90%
But they were such humanists.

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:53.330 align:middle line:84%
They were such lovers
of humans and life.

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:55.910 align:middle line:90%
But they saw us as victims.

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:58.730 align:middle line:84%
They thought that white
people had a disease

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:00.385 align:middle line:90%
that they called Wetiko.

00:09:00.385 --> 00:09:01.760 align:middle line:84%
And they thought
it was a disease

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:06.770 align:middle line:84%
of the spirit that led
us to just destroy things

00:09:06.770 --> 00:09:09.060 align:middle line:90%
unnecessarily.

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:11.510 align:middle line:10%
This kind of
dominator mentality,

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.260 align:middle line:10%
this domination of nature--

00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:16.500 align:middle line:10%
I mean, I'm trying to hold
on to that sensibility

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:20.250 align:middle line:10%
that, no, people are
not intrinsically evil,

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:22.590 align:middle line:10%
that we're in a system--

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:30.060 align:middle line:10%
we're living on a game, on a
landscape that is not natural.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:34.830 align:middle line:84%
So we ended up with this kind
of dehumanized view of people

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:38.370 align:middle line:84%
and this economy that
just-- by its very nature,

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:42.330 align:middle line:84%
an economy that had to grow
in order to keep working.

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:46.110 align:middle line:84%
So we started taking
stuff, just going to Africa

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.860 align:middle line:84%
and going to South America and
just expanding by any means

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:50.970 align:middle line:90%
necessary.

00:09:50.970 --> 00:09:52.800 align:middle line:10%
Really, as I see
it, that's the heart

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:55.920 align:middle line:10%
of Wetiko, of what
this disease is.

00:09:55.920 --> 00:10:02.820 align:middle line:84%
It's mistaking an operating
system, really, for reality.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And once you do that,
it's really hard

00:10:05.490 --> 00:10:07.120 align:middle line:90%
to see your way out of it.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:16.970 align:middle line:90%


00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:20.320 align:middle line:10%
The indigenous people
had a heightened ability

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:25.840 align:middle line:10%
to establish rapport that hadn't
been civilized out of them yet.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:29.350 align:middle line:84%
Making eye contact, being part
of an oral culture rather than

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:31.660 align:middle line:84%
a literate culture
or television culture

00:10:31.660 --> 00:10:39.340 align:middle line:84%
means that you engage with
people by making eye contact,

00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:41.890 align:middle line:84%
syncing up your breathing,
seeing if their pupils are

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:44.060 align:middle line:84%
getting larger or smaller
as you talk to them,

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:47.170 align:middle line:84%
seeing if your head is making
micro motions of agreement.

00:10:47.170 --> 00:10:50.830 align:middle line:84%
Then the oxytocin gets
released in my bloodstream.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:52.930 align:middle line:84%
My mirror neurons
start flashing.

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And it's a way of moving through
the world of always optimized

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:01.790 align:middle line:90%
for connection and rapport.

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:02.860 align:middle line:90%
And who is this?

00:11:02.860 --> 00:11:04.690 align:middle line:90%
How do we connect?

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:06.970 align:middle line:84%
And if they do that,
even if they're

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:09.370 align:middle line:84%
looking at a white
Western conquistador who's

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:12.335 align:middle line:84%
been told to take his sword
and start killing people,

00:11:12.335 --> 00:11:13.960 align:middle line:84%
they look in the eyes
and they see, oh,

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:17.890 align:middle line:84%
there's this human being there
that's being told to go kill

00:11:17.890 --> 00:11:20.710 align:middle line:84%
or to take, but,
wow, they're in pain.

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:22.600 align:middle line:90%
They're suffering.

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:24.340 align:middle line:90%
And how do I reach that person?

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:28.030 align:middle line:84%
Indigenous people are in an
altered state of consciousness.

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:29.410 align:middle line:10%
We're in this simulation.

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:31.630 align:middle line:10%
We're so removed from nature.

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:37.150 align:middle line:10%
We are in a CG
movie of the world.

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:40.390 align:middle line:84%
We're walking around like
Spock with our smartphones

00:11:40.390 --> 00:11:43.660 align:middle line:84%
like tricorders as if
we're on an alien planet.

00:11:43.660 --> 00:11:47.840 align:middle line:90%
That's how separate we are.

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:50.750 align:middle line:84%
>> We are not yet adapted
to living this way.

00:11:50.750 --> 00:11:53.600 align:middle line:84%
We don't really know
how to live this way.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:57.300 align:middle line:84%
We got domesticated and
didn't even realize it.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:12:01.450 align:middle line:84%
But unlike a dog, we wear more
of an invisible kind of collar

00:12:01.450 --> 00:12:03.740 align:middle line:84%
and an invisible
leash, because it's

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:06.620 align:middle line:84%
like an unseen hand,
where the dog knows

00:12:06.620 --> 00:12:09.860 align:middle line:84%
you're the master, telling
it what it can and can't do,

00:12:09.860 --> 00:12:11.750 align:middle line:84%
setting the rules
and feeding it.

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:14.420 align:middle line:84%
But we sort of have,
like-- we have a sense

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:17.150 align:middle line:90%
in our culture of our freedom.

00:12:17.150 --> 00:12:19.910 align:middle line:84%
But we're much more
like free range cattle

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:22.532 align:middle line:84%
than we are like free
human beings, told

00:12:22.532 --> 00:12:24.740 align:middle line:84%
that if we work hard we'll
have some kind of freedom.

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:26.750 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is, we all
know, as we become adults,

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:28.750 align:middle line:84%
it's kind of like a trap
and that you can't ever

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:29.810 align:middle line:90%
really get free.

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:31.910 align:middle line:84%
It'd be more fair to
say we're free range.

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:34.280 align:middle line:84%
So at this point,
human domestication

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:37.730 align:middle line:84%
is seven billion
people, most of whom

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:40.880 align:middle line:84%
live on a giant human
factory farm where

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:44.678 align:middle line:84%
we can move about freely, but
we don't have the true freedom

00:12:44.678 --> 00:12:46.220 align:middle line:84%
that hunter gatherers
had, and that's

00:12:46.220 --> 00:12:47.390 align:middle line:84%
the kind of freedom
most of us can't even

00:12:47.390 --> 00:12:48.853 align:middle line:90%
really imagine anymore.

00:12:48.853 --> 00:13:01.553 align:middle line:90%


00:13:01.553 --> 00:13:03.970 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, in most respects,
we're like the rest of life

00:13:03.970 --> 00:13:04.900 align:middle line:90%
on Earth.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:07.450 align:middle line:84%
It's interesting that,
particularly in the past 300

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:11.080 align:middle line:84%
years, so many people seem
to have forgotten that.

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:14.110 align:middle line:84%
Toni Morrison died recently,
the Nobel novelist.

00:13:14.110 --> 00:13:16.810 align:middle line:84%
She was saying that,
when she was growing up,

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:19.550 align:middle line:84%
animals weren't incidental
to people's lives.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:21.970 align:middle line:10%
They were intimately
connected with their lives,

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:25.690 align:middle line:10%
not as pets, but as part of
the ecosystem in which they

00:13:25.690 --> 00:13:27.430 align:middle line:10%
lived and depended.

00:13:27.430 --> 00:13:31.870 align:middle line:10%
Farmers had cattle and sheep and
not only that, other animals,

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:33.190 align:middle line:10%
which they knew by name.

00:13:33.190 --> 00:13:35.290 align:middle line:10%
And we had an
intimate relationship

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:37.570 align:middle line:10%
with the natural world
in every respect.

00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:39.310 align:middle line:10%
People understood the
pattern of seasons.

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:41.590 align:middle line:84%
They understood the pattern
of weather formations.

00:13:41.590 --> 00:13:44.770 align:middle line:84%
They understood intuitively
the different characteristics

00:13:44.770 --> 00:13:47.620 align:middle line:84%
and personalities almost of
animals they worked with,

00:13:47.620 --> 00:13:49.630 align:middle line:90%
depended upon, lived from.

00:13:49.630 --> 00:13:51.580 align:middle line:84%
They're an intimate part
of the human economy,

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:54.400 align:middle line:84%
as they still are in a
sense in parts of the world.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:57.310 align:middle line:84%
But then, in recent years, with
the growth of industrialism

00:13:57.310 --> 00:14:00.165 align:middle line:84%
and consumerism and the
systems of mass food production

00:14:00.165 --> 00:14:02.680 align:middle line:84%
and consumption, we've
become distanced from them.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:04.570 align:middle line:84%
Now our relationship
with animals

00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:08.110 align:middle line:84%
is reduced to often this rather
exaggerated sense of affection

00:14:08.110 --> 00:14:09.550 align:middle line:90%
for individual pets.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:12.130 align:middle line:10%
And people who have become
tremendously sentimental

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:14.230 align:middle line:10%
about household pets
will nonetheless

00:14:14.230 --> 00:14:17.680 align:middle line:10%
sit by and watch the mass
slaughter of animals for food

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:20.950 align:middle line:10%
and eat burgers at the table and
feed bits of them to their pets

00:14:20.950 --> 00:14:23.330 align:middle line:10%
with a kind of
dewy eyed sentiment

00:14:23.330 --> 00:14:26.500 align:middle line:10%
and not recognize the
carnage that's been wrought

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:28.355 align:middle line:10%
on the planet as a consequence.

00:14:28.355 --> 00:14:29.980 align:middle line:10%
Toni Morrison's point
was that, that we

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:32.830 align:middle line:10%
used to have this very intimate
relationship with animals

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:33.930 align:middle line:10%
in our ecosystem.

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:36.860 align:middle line:90%


00:14:36.860 --> 00:14:39.140 align:middle line:84%
Part of my point is,
in most respects,

00:14:39.140 --> 00:14:42.410 align:middle line:84%
we are just like the
rest of life on Earth.

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:45.740 align:middle line:84%
Most of the creatures, the
mammals and the higher order

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:47.210 align:middle line:90%
animals, have--

00:14:47.210 --> 00:14:50.510 align:middle line:84%
we know they have
feelings, sensibilities.

00:14:50.510 --> 00:14:51.800 align:middle line:90%
They have affections.

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:52.640 align:middle line:90%
They mourn.

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:53.510 align:middle line:90%
They grieve.

00:14:53.510 --> 00:14:56.130 align:middle line:90%
They exult. They raise children.

00:14:56.130 --> 00:14:58.340 align:middle line:84%
The fact they're a
different form of life

00:14:58.340 --> 00:15:00.738 align:middle line:84%
doesn't mean they're
separate from us

00:15:00.738 --> 00:15:02.030 align:middle line:90%
or that we should despise them.

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:03.660 align:middle line:90%
We know this to be true.

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:05.900 align:middle line:84%
But a big part of
what I'm marking for

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:07.850 align:middle line:84%
is that we should
restore those connections

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:10.872 align:middle line:84%
or at least restore our sense of
compassion for the rest of life

00:15:10.872 --> 00:15:12.830 align:middle line:84%
on Earth rather than
wreak the havoc against it

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:14.250 align:middle line:90%
that we're doing.

00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:16.250 align:middle line:84%
But there are-- clearly,
there are some respects

00:15:16.250 --> 00:15:17.485 align:middle line:90%
in which we are different.

00:15:17.485 --> 00:15:18.943 align:middle line:84%
And it would be
silly to deny them.

00:15:18.943 --> 00:15:21.920 align:middle line:84%
In fact, on the contrary, it
behooves us to understand them

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:24.170 align:middle line:90%
and to cultivate them.

00:15:24.170 --> 00:15:26.510 align:middle line:84%
For example, we are
sitting here surrounded

00:15:26.510 --> 00:15:28.220 align:middle line:90%
by advanced technology.

00:15:28.220 --> 00:15:30.110 align:middle line:84%
There are some things
that human beings

00:15:30.110 --> 00:15:33.125 align:middle line:84%
are capable of that no other
species has showed itself,

00:15:33.125 --> 00:15:34.250 align:middle line:90%
at least so far as we know.

00:15:34.250 --> 00:16:02.310 align:middle line:90%


00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:05.632 align:middle line:84%
It's hard to overestimate
the impact of industrialism.

00:16:05.632 --> 00:16:07.590 align:middle line:84%
Of course, it has its
roots in the 18th century

00:16:07.590 --> 00:16:11.250 align:middle line:84%
and a little earlier as a
force of economic change.

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:14.190 align:middle line:84%
But it led to a massive
shift in the way people

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:16.620 align:middle line:90%
lived and worked.

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:21.360 align:middle line:84%
The great majority of people
in Europe and in the Americas

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:23.430 align:middle line:90%
lived and worked in the fields.

00:16:23.430 --> 00:16:25.080 align:middle line:10%
But with industrialism,
they started

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:28.860 align:middle line:10%
to migrate into the cities
to work in the factories

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:30.728 align:middle line:10%
and to dig the roads
and build the railways

00:16:30.728 --> 00:16:32.520 align:middle line:10%
and create this massive
infrastructure that

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:33.820 align:middle line:10%
was required.

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:35.770 align:middle line:10%
And that needed a new
sort of workforce.

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:39.630 align:middle line:10%
It needed people who were
literate to a certain degree,

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:41.610 align:middle line:10%
who were numerate
to a certain degree.

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:44.970 align:middle line:84%
But it really was divided
into several groups.

00:16:44.970 --> 00:16:48.750 align:middle line:84%
The vast majority of people
during the industrial period

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:51.360 align:middle line:84%
were required to do manual
work, to tend the machines,

00:16:51.360 --> 00:16:55.080 align:middle line:84%
to wield the shovels, the
picks, and wield the hammers.

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:58.180 align:middle line:90%


00:16:58.180 --> 00:17:01.030 align:middle line:84%
>> The hallmark
of industrialism,

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:03.940 align:middle line:84%
really more than the steam
engine or anything else,

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:04.900 align:middle line:90%
is the clock.

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:06.970 align:middle line:84%
The power of the clock
in the Industrial Age

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:09.460 align:middle line:84%
is that, before
the Industrial Age,

00:17:09.460 --> 00:17:14.140 align:middle line:84%
people would create
value and exchange it.

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:16.480 align:middle line:84%
I'll make a candle
or make some shoes

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:19.510 align:middle line:84%
and bring it to market and
exchange it with someone else.

00:17:19.510 --> 00:17:21.970 align:middle line:84%
And when the Industrial
Age happened,

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:25.540 align:middle line:84%
what it was really about
was disconnecting people

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:27.400 align:middle line:90%
from the value they created.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:32.260 align:middle line:10%
So instead of me making a pair
of shoes and selling them,

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:35.200 align:middle line:10%
now it's me going to
work at a factory,

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:37.570 align:middle line:10%
nailing one nail into
the bottom of a shoe

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:39.610 align:middle line:10%
and handing it over
to the next guy.

00:17:39.610 --> 00:17:43.960 align:middle line:84%
And instead of selling my
value, I'm selling my time.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm working by the hour.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.270 align:middle line:84%
They put the clock up on the
clock tower as if to say, look,

00:17:49.270 --> 00:17:50.380 align:middle line:90%
it's all fair.

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:51.640 align:middle line:90%
An hour is an hour.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:52.990 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that just?

00:17:52.990 --> 00:17:56.200 align:middle line:84%
But what's intrinsically
unfair is that I'm not

00:17:56.200 --> 00:17:57.910 align:middle line:90%
allowed to create value.

00:17:57.910 --> 00:17:59.680 align:middle line:84%
I'm only allowed
to sell my time.

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:02.810 align:middle line:84%
And now, 500 years
later, 600 years later,

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:04.428 align:middle line:84%
we see it as, well,
that's employment.

00:18:04.428 --> 00:18:06.220 align:middle line:84%
You just get a job,
and that's what you do.

00:18:06.220 --> 00:18:07.420 align:middle line:90%
You work 40 hours a week.

00:18:07.420 --> 00:18:11.330 align:middle line:10%
It's like, no, but
that's sort of the moment

00:18:11.330 --> 00:18:15.890 align:middle line:10%
that time is money was born,
because time was money.

00:18:15.890 --> 00:18:17.180 align:middle line:90%
It was all about time.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:20.350 align:middle line:84%
And then the only metric
that tends to matter

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:21.490 align:middle line:90%
is the efficiency.

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:25.270 align:middle line:84%
How much work can I get out
of someone in that hour?

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:28.100 align:middle line:84%
How much value can I
extract in that hour?

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:29.800 align:middle line:84%
So I want to increase
the efficiency.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:31.960 align:middle line:84%
And you'd stand next to
workers with a stopwatch

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:33.460 align:middle line:84%
and see, how many
nails can they put

00:18:33.460 --> 00:18:35.330 align:middle line:84%
in the bottom of that
shoe in 30 seconds?

00:18:35.330 --> 00:18:36.340 align:middle line:90%
Well, get it down to 28.

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:37.630 align:middle line:90%
Get it down to 20.

00:18:37.630 --> 00:18:42.430 align:middle line:84%
Once we start looking at people
as mechanisms through which we

00:18:42.430 --> 00:18:46.030 align:middle line:84%
extract value,
then it wasn't too

00:18:46.030 --> 00:18:50.670 align:middle line:84%
long until our education system
kind of flipped on its head.

00:18:50.670 --> 00:18:52.420 align:middle line:84%
The public education
was originally

00:18:52.420 --> 00:18:55.930 align:middle line:84%
invented as kind of a
mercy or a compensation.

00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:58.780 align:middle line:10%
It was so that the coal
miner could come home

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:02.140 align:middle line:10%
after a day of work and
be able to read a novel

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:04.690 align:middle line:10%
and appreciate it or be
able to read the paper

00:19:04.690 --> 00:19:08.440 align:middle line:10%
and then vote effectively
or intelligently.

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:12.310 align:middle line:10%
It was compensation
for a life of hard work

00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:16.240 align:middle line:10%
so you could have the dignity
of having a mind that actually

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:17.230 align:middle line:10%
functioned.

00:19:17.230 --> 00:19:20.710 align:middle line:84%
But slowly, over time and
I guess because of time

00:19:20.710 --> 00:19:23.650 align:middle line:84%
and the value of
efficiency, we started

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:30.183 align:middle line:84%
to externalize job training
to public education.

00:19:30.183 --> 00:19:31.600 align:middle line:84%
>> There have
always been schools.

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:35.422 align:middle line:84%
People have always been able
to get themselves educated.

00:19:35.422 --> 00:19:36.880 align:middle line:84%
What we're really
talking about are

00:19:36.880 --> 00:19:40.420 align:middle line:84%
the growth of systems of
mass public education.

00:19:40.420 --> 00:19:42.820 align:middle line:84%
And they really
have their origins

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:47.170 align:middle line:84%
in most countries in the
sort of mid 19th century.

00:19:47.170 --> 00:19:49.960 align:middle line:84%
By mass public education,
I mean systems of education

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:53.710 align:middle line:84%
that were initiated by
central governments, which

00:19:53.710 --> 00:19:57.880 align:middle line:84%
were available, sort of free at
the point of delivery in most

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:02.170 align:middle line:84%
cases, and, in due
course, were compulsory

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:04.150 align:middle line:90%
for certain age groups.

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:07.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean, really, historically,
they're relatively recent.

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:09.790 align:middle line:84%
These systems, in my view-- and
I've written quite a bit about

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:10.920 align:middle line:90%
it--

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:14.680 align:middle line:84%
grew up in the interests of
the Industrial Revolution

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:17.250 align:middle line:84%
and, to some degree,
in the image of it.

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:21.370 align:middle line:84%
They grew up because
of a need in part

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:27.220 align:middle line:84%
to create a mass workforce for
this huge industrial complex

00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:29.710 align:middle line:84%
that was evolving,
because the rough equation

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:31.713 align:middle line:84%
was that about
80% of people were

00:20:31.713 --> 00:20:33.380 align:middle line:84%
going to be selling
their physical labor

00:20:33.380 --> 00:20:35.950 align:middle line:84%
and maybe 20% would be selling
their intellectual labor.

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:37.270 align:middle line:90%
And it was built that way.

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:39.400 align:middle line:84%
So there was an
economic impulse.

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:40.910 align:middle line:90%
That's the first thing.

00:20:40.910 --> 00:20:42.760 align:middle line:84%
The second thing
is that the system

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:46.220 align:middle line:84%
was organized a bit on the
principles of mass production.

00:20:46.220 --> 00:20:48.470 align:middle line:84%
So people were selected
for certain roots.

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:51.760 align:middle line:84%
Their kids went through
the system by age group.

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:55.010 align:middle line:84%
This was a massive invention
to put the system into place.

00:20:55.010 --> 00:20:58.290 align:middle line:10%
But children were-- they went in
at a certain age, four or five.

00:20:58.290 --> 00:20:59.920 align:middle line:84%
They then went
through by age group.

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:01.300 align:middle line:90%
They still do.

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:02.890 align:middle line:84%
There are certain
points of selection

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:05.322 align:middle line:84%
where some kids go that
way, some kids go that way.

00:21:05.322 --> 00:21:07.780 align:middle line:84%
People were selected according
to whether they were thought

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:09.670 align:middle line:90%
to be more fit for manual work.

00:21:09.670 --> 00:21:13.360 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they might have the
sort of spark they thought

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:16.540 align:middle line:84%
was needed for academic work or
a particular interest in that.

00:21:16.540 --> 00:21:19.300 align:middle line:84%
But they were sort of
divided into sheep and goats.

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:22.630 align:middle line:84%
And then a few people went on
to university as a consequence.

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:26.560 align:middle line:84%
So the organizational
principle was

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:29.560 align:middle line:84%
very similar to mass
production systems.

00:21:29.560 --> 00:21:32.650 align:middle line:84%
It was based on standardization,
conformity, selection,

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:34.780 align:middle line:84%
and it was also
geared to selecting

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:39.010 align:middle line:84%
a particular type of commodity
with a particular sort

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:41.360 align:middle line:90%
of product at the far end.

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:43.733 align:middle line:84%
So what you had evolving
over that period

00:21:43.733 --> 00:21:44.650 align:middle line:90%
was a kind of pyramid.

00:21:44.650 --> 00:21:47.470 align:middle line:10%
There was a broad base of
people who were doing--

00:21:47.470 --> 00:21:50.410 align:middle line:10%
who were being educated to a
certain level of basic numeracy

00:21:50.410 --> 00:21:51.790 align:middle line:10%
and literacy.

00:21:51.790 --> 00:21:54.010 align:middle line:84%
There was a group
slightly higher

00:21:54.010 --> 00:21:56.260 align:middle line:84%
than that who would be going
on to administrative work

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:57.968 align:middle line:84%
and certain sorts of
managerial type jobs

00:21:57.968 --> 00:21:59.690 align:middle line:84%
and then a group that
would be educated

00:21:59.690 --> 00:22:02.270 align:middle line:84%
to take on these sort of
higher leadership roles.

00:22:02.270 --> 00:22:04.400 align:middle line:84%
And the system was
composed in that image--

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:05.930 align:middle line:84%
broad base of
elementary education,

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:10.070 align:middle line:84%
the slightly narrow band of sort
of high school, middle school

00:22:10.070 --> 00:22:13.070 align:middle line:84%
and high school, and then
quite a narrow band of people

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:15.470 align:middle line:90%
who went on to university.

00:22:15.470 --> 00:22:19.100 align:middle line:84%
And like any system of
mass industrial production,

00:22:19.100 --> 00:22:22.490 align:middle line:84%
it was predicated on generating
a fair amount of waste

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:26.600 align:middle line:84%
materials because not everybody
was suited to the task

00:22:26.600 --> 00:22:28.460 align:middle line:84%
that they were
being groomed for,

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:29.730 align:middle line:90%
and so they went to one side.

00:22:29.730 --> 00:22:32.390 align:middle line:84%
And I think it was at that
point we invented the whole idea

00:22:32.390 --> 00:22:34.775 align:middle line:90%
of educational disability.

00:22:34.775 --> 00:22:35.900 align:middle line:90%
>> I mean, there's a model.

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:38.480 align:middle line:10%
It's the Prussian
model of education

00:22:38.480 --> 00:22:41.270 align:middle line:10%
where the school is
modeled after the factory

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:45.170 align:middle line:10%
with bells ringing after
each period and the teachers

00:22:45.170 --> 00:22:48.920 align:middle line:10%
like the foremen and the
students follow the directions.

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:52.970 align:middle line:10%
So now we've got the
principals of our high schools

00:22:52.970 --> 00:22:55.160 align:middle line:10%
and the presidents of
our colleges meeting

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:59.990 align:middle line:10%
with the CEOs of
corporations to find out,

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:02.940 align:middle line:10%
what do you want our
students to learn?

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:05.690 align:middle line:10%
What do you want them to
know so they can get jobs?

00:23:05.690 --> 00:23:07.070 align:middle line:10%
How do you want
us to train them?

00:23:07.070 --> 00:23:11.600 align:middle line:10%
So corporations are just
externalizing employee training

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:14.290 align:middle line:10%
to the schools.

00:23:14.290 --> 00:23:17.410 align:middle line:84%
If anything, you're doing
the opposite of education.

00:23:17.410 --> 00:23:22.960 align:middle line:84%
You're not creating inquisitive,
open, creative, disruptive

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:23.800 align:middle line:90%
minds.

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:27.370 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to
favor liberal arts.

00:23:27.370 --> 00:23:29.350 align:middle line:84%
In a modern age,
this is where we

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:31.300 align:middle line:90%
get what we keep calling STEM.

00:23:31.300 --> 00:23:34.940 align:middle line:84%
This is science, technology,
engineering, and mathematics.

00:23:34.940 --> 00:23:35.740 align:middle line:90%
Beautiful.

00:23:35.740 --> 00:23:37.900 align:middle line:84%
But why do we want
to teach STEM--

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:39.650 align:middle line:84%
so that they learn
how to program

00:23:39.650 --> 00:23:42.820 align:middle line:84%
so they can go and make
computers for Silicon Valley

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:44.462 align:middle line:90%
and get jobs.

00:23:44.462 --> 00:23:46.420 align:middle line:84%
No, we don't want them
to learn the humanities,

00:23:46.420 --> 00:23:47.590 align:middle line:90%
because then what?

00:23:47.590 --> 00:23:50.070 align:middle line:84%
Then they're going to start
to question the whole thing.

00:23:50.070 --> 00:23:54.330 align:middle line:84%
Critical thinking makes
you look outside the frame

00:23:54.330 --> 00:23:56.820 align:middle line:84%
of corporate capitalism and
say, well, wait a minute,

00:23:56.820 --> 00:23:58.590 align:middle line:90%
where's the meaning in this?

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:00.240 align:middle line:90%
What's the future in this?

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:04.080 align:middle line:84%
What are we externalizing
to nature, to women,

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:05.670 align:middle line:90%
to other people?

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:09.510 align:middle line:84%
So unless you are able
to do critical thinking,

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:10.650 align:middle line:90%
you're not educated at all.

00:24:10.650 --> 00:24:14.475 align:middle line:90%


00:24:14.475 --> 00:24:17.100 align:middle line:84%
>> It's one of the reasons why
I think it's very important that

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:22.020 align:middle line:84%
we move away from some idea of
standardization and conformity

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:26.130 align:middle line:84%
and recognize that individual
achievement, individual values,

00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:29.670 align:middle line:84%
individual potential in lives
are as various as the people

00:24:29.670 --> 00:24:31.350 align:middle line:90%
we're talking about.

00:24:31.350 --> 00:24:33.240 align:middle line:84%
Education has to
become individualized.

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:34.980 align:middle line:84%
And if you
standardize it, you're

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:38.790 align:middle line:84%
bound to create a catastrophe
for some people that

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:41.705 align:middle line:84%
would be avoidable if you
saw them as individuals.

00:24:41.705 --> 00:24:57.225 align:middle line:90%


00:24:57.225 --> 00:25:01.810 align:middle line:84%
A wonderful woman, when
she was a young kid

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:06.188 align:middle line:84%
in elementary school,
was in constant trouble.

00:25:06.188 --> 00:25:07.230 align:middle line:90%
She didn't pay attention.

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:08.860 align:middle line:84%
She fidgeted a
great deal and tend

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:11.850 align:middle line:90%
to get up and wander around.

00:25:11.850 --> 00:25:13.648 align:middle line:84%
Eventually, the school
contacted her mother

00:25:13.648 --> 00:25:15.690 align:middle line:84%
and said that they thought
Gillian had a learning

00:25:15.690 --> 00:25:16.210 align:middle line:90%
difficulty.

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:18.043 align:middle line:84%
And they explained to
her what she should do

00:25:18.043 --> 00:25:20.340 align:middle line:84%
and that she should take
Gillian to see a specialist.

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:22.668 align:middle line:84%
And her mother was naturally
devastated to hear that.

00:25:22.668 --> 00:25:24.210 align:middle line:84%
He asked to go and
sit at the far end

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:25.890 align:middle line:84%
of the room on
this leather sofa,

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:28.200 align:middle line:84%
and he talked to her mother
about all the problems

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:31.820 align:middle line:84%
Gillian was having and
asked her to describe them.

00:25:31.820 --> 00:25:34.670 align:middle line:84%
And she said, all this time that
her mother was speaking to him,

00:25:34.670 --> 00:25:36.283 align:middle line:90%
he was staring at Gillian.

00:25:36.283 --> 00:25:37.700 align:middle line:84%
And she said, I
was uncomfortable,

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:39.830 align:middle line:84%
and I was sitting on my
hands so I wouldn't fidget.

00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:41.360 align:middle line:84%
This went on for
several minutes.

00:25:41.360 --> 00:25:43.193 align:middle line:84%
And then he stood up
and he said to Gillian,

00:25:43.193 --> 00:25:45.500 align:middle line:84%
look, this has been
very interesting,

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:48.380 align:middle line:84%
Gillian, but I need to speak
to your mother privately now.

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:50.600 align:middle line:84%
So if you wait here,
we're going to leave you,

00:25:50.600 --> 00:25:51.400 align:middle line:90%
but we'll be back.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:52.483 align:middle line:90%
We won't be very far away.

00:25:52.483 --> 00:25:54.220 align:middle line:84%
We'll come back
in a few minutes.

00:25:54.220 --> 00:25:56.510 align:middle line:84%
And she said they got
up and they went out.

00:25:56.510 --> 00:25:58.700 align:middle line:84%
But as they went out, he
leaned across his desk

00:25:58.700 --> 00:26:01.276 align:middle line:90%
and turned the radio on.

00:26:01.276 --> 00:26:02.982 align:middle line:84%
And he got into the
car, apparently,

00:26:02.982 --> 00:26:05.190 align:middle line:84%
and he turned to her mother
and said, just stand here

00:26:05.190 --> 00:26:06.315 align:middle line:90%
for a moment and watch her.

00:26:06.315 --> 00:26:07.330 align:middle line:90%
See what she does.

00:26:07.330 --> 00:26:09.850 align:middle line:84%
She said there was a
window back into the room.

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:12.773 align:middle line:84%
So she couldn't see them,
but they could see her.

00:26:12.773 --> 00:26:14.690 align:middle line:84%
She said the minute they
were out of the room,

00:26:14.690 --> 00:26:17.000 align:middle line:84%
she was on their feet
moving to the music.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.490 align:middle line:84%
She said she danced
around on top of the sofa

00:26:19.490 --> 00:26:21.620 align:middle line:90%
and on the tables.

00:26:21.620 --> 00:26:25.180 align:middle line:84%
And she said, because she'd
been sitting still for so long.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:26.930 align:middle line:84%
They watched this for
a couple of minutes,

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:29.120 align:middle line:84%
and he turned to mother,
and he said, you know,

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:31.490 align:middle line:90%
Mrs. Lynne, Gillian isn't sick.

00:26:31.490 --> 00:26:32.990 align:middle line:90%
She's a dancer.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:35.798 align:middle line:90%
Take her to a dance school.

00:26:35.798 --> 00:26:37.640 align:middle line:90%
And she did.

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:39.890 align:middle line:84%
She went to the
Royal Ballet School.

00:26:39.890 --> 00:26:43.452 align:middle line:84%
And she said, I
walked into this room.

00:26:43.452 --> 00:26:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And she said, I'll
never forget it.

00:26:44.910 --> 00:26:48.590 align:middle line:84%
It was full of people like me,
people who couldn't sit still

00:26:48.590 --> 00:26:52.630 align:middle line:84%
and, as she put it, people
who have to move to think.

00:26:52.630 --> 00:26:54.940 align:middle line:84%
She was eventually accepted
into the Royal Ballet,

00:26:54.940 --> 00:26:57.940 align:middle line:84%
and then she became a soloist,
a principal and a soloist,

00:26:57.940 --> 00:27:00.100 align:middle line:84%
and had a wonderful career
at the Royal Ballet,

00:27:00.100 --> 00:27:02.200 align:middle line:90%
traveled the world with them.

00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:03.970 align:middle line:84%
And then, when she
left, she formed

00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:06.270 align:middle line:84%
her own company, the
Gillian Lynne Dance Company,

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:08.770 align:middle line:84%
put all kinds of productions
on in Broadway in the West End.

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:10.720 align:middle line:84%
And then she met
Andrew Lloyd Webber

00:27:10.720 --> 00:27:12.610 align:middle line:84%
as an accomplished and
very successful dancer

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:14.380 align:middle line:90%
and choreographer at this point.

00:27:14.380 --> 00:27:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And Andrew asked if
she would choreograph

00:27:16.270 --> 00:27:19.120 align:middle line:84%
"Cats," which she did,
and "Phantom of the Opera"

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:20.410 align:middle line:90%
and other of his productions.

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:23.080 align:middle line:84%
She became his
principal choreographer.

00:27:23.080 --> 00:27:25.960 align:middle line:10%
She went on to give
pleasure to millions

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:28.240 align:middle line:10%
and became a multi-millionaire.

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:32.020 align:middle line:10%
And it's perfectly possible
these days that somebody else

00:27:32.020 --> 00:27:35.740 align:middle line:10%
would tell her to sit down, calm
down, and take these tablets.

00:27:35.740 --> 00:27:37.130 align:middle line:90%
And she wasn't sick.

00:27:37.130 --> 00:27:37.930 align:middle line:90%
She was a dancer.

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:40.120 align:middle line:84%
And I feel this for an
awful lot of people,

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:44.605 align:middle line:84%
that if you stereotype people
against a very narrow view

00:27:44.605 --> 00:27:47.710 align:middle line:84%
of ability, then
you automatically

00:27:47.710 --> 00:27:50.950 align:middle line:84%
generate a very big
conception of inability

00:27:50.950 --> 00:27:53.950 align:middle line:90%
and, at worst, of disability.

00:27:53.950 --> 00:27:56.620 align:middle line:84%
A lot of what goes on
in our school systems

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:58.570 align:middle line:84%
is not the result
of legislation.

00:27:58.570 --> 00:28:02.680 align:middle line:84%
It's the result of
habit and ritual.

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:05.230 align:middle line:84%
There is nothing anywhere,
really, in most of our systems

00:28:05.230 --> 00:28:07.630 align:middle line:84%
that requires that we
educate kids by age group.

00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:09.770 align:middle line:84%
We just do because
we think you have to.

00:28:09.770 --> 00:28:11.934 align:middle line:90%
But you don't.

00:28:11.934 --> 00:28:15.770 align:middle line:84%
And outside the schools, we
wouldn't think of doing that.

00:28:15.770 --> 00:28:17.290 align:middle line:84%
When kids leave
school at 3 o'clock

00:28:17.290 --> 00:28:19.000 align:middle line:84%
in the afternoon
or 4 o'clock, we

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.710 align:middle line:84%
don't say, now, all
the four-year-olds

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:22.538 align:middle line:90%
be sure to go over there.

00:28:22.538 --> 00:28:23.830 align:middle line:90%
Keep away from eight-year-olds.

00:28:23.830 --> 00:28:26.590 align:middle line:90%
Bad things happen, we know.

00:28:26.590 --> 00:28:31.390 align:middle line:84%
Communities are
intergenerational.

00:28:31.390 --> 00:28:33.670 align:middle line:84%
We don't have to divide
the day into subjects.

00:28:33.670 --> 00:28:34.690 align:middle line:90%
We just do.

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:35.630 align:middle line:90%
You don't have to.

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:37.713 align:middle line:84%
There are lots of great
schools that don't do that

00:28:37.713 --> 00:28:44.290 align:middle line:84%
and having wonderful
success as a result.

00:28:44.290 --> 00:28:49.540 align:middle line:84%
Creativity is one of the
defining characteristics

00:28:49.540 --> 00:28:51.460 align:middle line:90%
of our species.

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:55.960 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the things
that makes us human.

00:28:55.960 --> 00:29:00.105 align:middle line:84%
We create the lives that we live
through the possibilities we

00:29:00.105 --> 00:29:01.480 align:middle line:84%
see and the
opportunities we take

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:02.740 align:middle line:90%
or the ones we step away from.

00:29:02.740 --> 00:29:04.870 align:middle line:84%
It's how people's
lives are transformed

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:07.390 align:middle line:84%
by discovering a
talent and the passion

00:29:07.390 --> 00:29:09.370 align:middle line:84%
and the purpose
that goes with it.

00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:11.830 align:middle line:84%
That's what the Gillian
Lynne story is about.

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:18.060 align:middle line:84%
Creativity, in other words,
isn't some exotic byproduct

00:29:18.060 --> 00:29:20.280 align:middle line:84%
that happens to be
present in a few people.

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:22.480 align:middle line:84%
We've come to think
of it that way.

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:23.580 align:middle line:90%
But it's not true.

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:27.210 align:middle line:84%
Creativity is the
pulse of human life.

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:32.250 align:middle line:84%
We live in a city that wasn't
here 150 years ago like this.

00:29:32.250 --> 00:29:36.000 align:middle line:84%
This is being created by the
interplay of millions of minds

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.790 align:middle line:84%
working together,
collaborating, where all of us

00:29:38.790 --> 00:29:42.570 align:middle line:84%
now based in the great
net of the world wide web

00:29:42.570 --> 00:29:44.130 align:middle line:90%
and all of its works.

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:46.377 align:middle line:10%
This is new to our generation.

00:29:46.377 --> 00:29:47.460 align:middle line:90%
This didn't happen before.

00:29:47.460 --> 00:29:48.543 align:middle line:90%
It didn't come into being.

00:29:48.543 --> 00:29:51.180 align:middle line:84%
It's not-- it didn't come
around like the oceans.

00:29:51.180 --> 00:29:52.028 align:middle line:90%
We made this.

00:29:52.028 --> 00:29:53.820 align:middle line:84%
Somebody designed the
clothes that we wear.

00:29:53.820 --> 00:29:58.530 align:middle line:84%
Creativity is what contributes
to the nature of our humanity.

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:01.170 align:middle line:84%
We can use it and
we can misuse it.

00:30:01.170 --> 00:30:07.050 align:middle line:84%
So, to me, saying that
education should cultivate

00:30:07.050 --> 00:30:11.730 align:middle line:84%
children's creative
capacities isn't

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:15.480 align:middle line:84%
kind of an appeal to
have some extra hour

00:30:15.480 --> 00:30:18.960 align:middle line:84%
of free play-based activities
on a Friday afternoon,

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:21.480 align:middle line:84%
though I think we should have
free play-based activities

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:22.800 align:middle line:90%
on a Friday afternoon.

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:25.950 align:middle line:84%
It's to recognize that
there is a set of capacities

00:30:25.950 --> 00:30:27.840 align:middle line:84%
here, which isn't
separate from, but it's

00:30:27.840 --> 00:30:29.670 align:middle line:84%
integrated with everything
else that we do.

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:40.960 align:middle line:90%


00:30:40.960 --> 00:30:44.680 align:middle line:84%
